  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Lucia Weston writes that Dr. and Mrs. Charles Theodor C. Follen called while Maria Weston Chapman was away at Taunton. Lucia commented: &quot;Mrs. Follen seemed to think a great deal of Dr. [William Ellery] Channing&apos;s book.&quot; Lucia compares the seamen&apos;s fair with the anti-slavery fair. She comments on the letters from Angelina and Sarah Grimke to the [Samuel] Philbricks as &quot;the most ludicrous stuff.&quot; Angelina has not made up her mind and wants facts. Maria Weston Chapman went to Lynn to deliver a speech and returned the next morning, having given &quot;general satisfaction.&quot; John A. Collins is worn out collecting money from Lynn. Lucia said: &quot;We have found out that Lynn the last year has given a thousand and odd dollars to the cause.&quot; Maria Weston Chapman will probably not go to New York; Henry G. Chapman cannot go on his father&apos;s account. Lucia said: &quot;The pledge is going to be paid the first day of May.</subfield>
